<font color="#FF0000">ADDITIONAL THOUGHT</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun  2  1:32:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To All,<br>
By the way, I understand the Uniform Code of Military Justice.  A lawful order can't be refused and punishment can be taken (the good old Article 15).  I also understand that refusing an order in wartime condition can be deadly and wrong.  But how much is enough?  When a order in a combat situation is stupid or harmful, how can a soldier be expected to follow? I don't buy that Charge of the Light Brigade poem philosophy-&quot;their's not to reason why, their's but to do or die&quot;.
<p><code>--   (Joe DeLeva) </code><p>


